RRT Exploration with Key-Door Mechanism

We consider an explorer robot that starts from an initial position and aims to cover as much of the maze as possible using the RRT (Rapidly-exploring Random Tree) algorithm.

Problem Description
The robot's exploration is initially blocked by a door (represented as a red cube).
The door can only be opened if the robot reaches a key (represented as a yellow sphere).
Once the robot reaches the key, the door opens, allowing access to previously unreachable areas of the maze.
Assumptions
The robot is allowed to sample configurations across the entire maze.
If the connect function attempts to extend the tree toward a region behind the closed door, it fails and returns False.
After the door is opened, the connect function operates normally without restrictions.
Both the door and the key are non-physical (non-colliding) objects; they serve only as visual markers in the environment.
Objective

Modify and extend the provided lab code to implement the above scenario and maximize the area coverage of the maze using RRT.

Coverage Metric
The maze is divided into cells.
A cell is considered visited if there exists at least one node of the RRT tree within a radius of 0.1 meters from the center of that cell.
Report the percentage of the maze covered by the RRT.
Simulation Task (MuJoCo)

Using the provided controller, simulate the following trajectory in MuJoCo:

Start position →
Key location →
A target point that was not accessible before the door was opened
